+# Firebase Setup Guide
+
+## Fixing the "Permission denied on resource project yoga-booking-app" Error
+
+The error you're seeing is because the Firestore security rules in your Firebase project are not allowing access to the database. Follow these steps to update the security rules:
+
+### Step 1: Access Firebase Console
+1. Go to [Firebase Console](https://console.firebase.google.com/)
+2. Select your project: "yoga-booking-app"
+
+### Step 2: Update Firestore Security Rules
+1. In the left sidebar, click on "Firestore Database"
+2. Click on the "Rules" tab
+3. Replace the existing rules with the content from the `firestore_security_rules.txt` file
+4. Click "Publish" to save the changes
+
+### Step 3: Create Test Collection (Optional)
+1. While in Firestore Database, click on the "Data" tab
+2. Click "Start collection"
+3. Name the collection "test_connection"
+4. Add a document with a random ID (or click "Auto-ID")
+5. Add a field: Name: "test", Value: "true", Type: string
+6. Click "Save"
+
+### Step 4: Verify Firebase Authentication (If Using Auth)
+1. In the left sidebar, click on "Authentication"
+2. Make sure the authentication methods you need are enabled
+3. If you're using email/password authentication, you may need to create a test user
+
+### Step 5: Check Firebase Project Settings
+1. In the left sidebar, click on "Project settings" (gear icon)
+2. Under "Your apps", verify that both your Android and Flutter apps are registered
+3. Make sure the package names match what's in your code:
+ - Android app: "com.example.myapplication"
+ - Flutter app: "com.example.cwcustomerapp"
+
+### Step 6: Test Your Apps Again
+After making these changes, run both your Android and Flutter apps again to see if the permission issue is resolved.
+
+## Security Note
+The security rules provided in `firestore_security_rules.txt` allow unrestricted access to your Firestore database. This is fine for development and testing, but for a production app, you should implement proper authentication and more restrictive security rules.
+
+## Additional Troubleshooting
+If you're still having issues after updating the security rules:
+
+1. Check the Firebase console logs for any errors
+2. Verify that your google-services.json files have the correct project ID
+3. Make sure your apps have internet permission in the manifest
+4. Try clearing the app data or reinstalling the apps
+5. Check if there are any billing issues with your Firebase project","refToolCallId":"toolu_01NJtfUUJyn7NZASUVxekkJf"},{"type":"text","text":"Now, let's also create a simple test script that you can run to verify the Firestore connection after updating the security rules:"},{"type":"toolCall","toolCallId":"toolu_014o5Zfy4yev1MdvLafbvPoB","statusText":"Change generated","status":"SUCCESS","context":{"files":[{"path":"comp1786cw/lib/firebase_test.dart","fsPath":"/Users/macmini/AndroidStudioProjects/comp1786/comp1786cw/lib/firebase_test.dart"}]},"isHidden":false},{"type":"codeHunk","lineBasedDiff":"--- comp1786cw/lib/firebase_test.dart
