+# Firebase Setup Guide%0A%0A## Fixing the %22Permission denied on resource project yoga-booking-app%22 Error%0A%0AThe error you're seeing is because the Firestore security rules in your Firebase project are not allowing access to the database. Follow these steps to update the security rules:%0A%0A### Step 1: Access Firebase Console%0A1. Go to %5BFirebase Console%5D(https://console.firebase.google.com/)%0A2. Select your project: %22yoga-booking-app%22%0A%0A### Step 2: Update Firestore Security Rules%0A1. In the left sidebar, click on %22Firestore Database%22%0A2. Click on the %22Rules%22 tab%0A3. Replace the existing rules with the content from the %60firestore_security_rules.txt%60 file%0A4. Click %22Publish%22 to save the changes%0A%0A### Step 3: Create Test Collection (Optional)%0A1. While in Firestore Database, click on the %22Data%22 tab%0A2. Click %22Start collection%22%0A3. Name the collection %22test_connection%22%0A4. Add a document with a random ID (or click %22Auto-ID%22)%0A5. Add a field: Name: %22test%22, Value: %22true%22, Type: string%0A6. Click %22Save%22%0A%0A### Step 4: Verify Firebase Authentication (If Using Auth)%0A1. In the left sidebar, click on %22Authentication%22%0A2. Make sure the authentication methods you need are enabled%0A3. If you're using email/password authentication, you may need to create a test user%0A%0A### Step 5: Check Firebase Project Settings%0A1. In the left sidebar, click on %22Project settings%22 (gear icon)%0A2. Under %22Your apps%22, verify that both your Android and Flutter apps are registered%0A3. Make sure the package names match what's in your code:%0A - Android app: %22com.example.myapplication%22%0A - Flutter app: %22com.example.cwcustomerapp%22%0A%0A### Step 6: Test Your Apps Again%0AAfter making these changes, run both your Android and Flutter apps again to see if the permission issue is resolved.%0A%0A## Security Note%0AThe security rules provided in %60firestore_security_rules.txt%60 allow unrestricted access to your Firestore database. This is fine for development and testing, but for a production app, you should implement proper authentication and more restrictive security rules.%0A%0A## Additional Troubleshooting%0AIf you're still having issues after updating the security rules:%0A%0A1. Check the Firebase console logs for any errors%0A2. Verify that your google-services.json files have the correct project ID%0A3. Make sure your apps have internet permission in the manifest%0A4. Try clearing the app data or reinstalling the apps%0A5. Check if there are any billing issues with your Firebase project
